        <tr class="cells">
            <td><a href='@String.Format("{0}TaxAccArticle1", Model.BaseUrl)' target="_blank">COVID-19 and claiming benefits</a></td>

            <td>If the employee is employed by one employer on 19 March but is transferred to another employer under the TUPE scheme later, they can be furloughed by the new employer.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>How can I prepare for any future lockdown? </td>
            <td>It is advisable to anticipate potential lockdown periods in the future by implementing a lay-off (short-time working) clause into the employment contracts.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>Can public sector employees be furloughed? </td>
            <td>Public sector employees are not expected to be furloughed. This is because they are usually required to provide essential services. However, this is not a hard rule and if they are not providing essential services they can be furloughed.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>How much can I claim under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </td>
            <td>Employers can claim 80% of an employee's salary up to &pound;,500 per month. In addition, you can claim Employer National Insurance contributions and auto-enrolment pension contributions that are payable at a reduced rate.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>To be eligible for the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme, do I need to prove that I cannot otherwise pay employees ? </td>
            <td>It is not a requirement that the employer cannot otherwise pay its employees or that they need to make employees redundant. An employer can furlough workers if the instruction is given by reason of circumstances arising as a result of coronavirus or coronavirus disease.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>What information do I need to submit to apply to the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </td>
            <td>The Government has published a step-by-step guide. https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/884664/Coronavirus_Job_Retention_Scheme_step_by_step_guide_for_employers.pdf. The information required is: 1. The number of employees to be furloughed; 2. The dates from and to which employees have been furloughed; 3. Details of employees - the name and National Insurance Number of each furloughed employee; 4. Your employer PAYE scheme reference number; 5. Your Corporation Tax Unique Taxpayer Reference, Self-Assessment Unique Taxpayer Reference or Company Registration Number as appropriate for your entity; 6. Your UK bank account details; 7. Your organisation's registered name; 8. Your organisation's address</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>To apply to the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme, what steps will I need to take? </td>
            <td>To use the scheme, you need to take 5 steps.:1. check if you can claim.2. check which employees you can put on furlough.3. calculate 80% of your employees� wages.4. claim for your employees� wages.5. report a payment in PAYE Real Time Information.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>Do employers need a written agrement with their employees to be eligible for furlough pay? </td>
            <td>Initially, to be eligible for making an application under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme, the original Direction stated that employers must have obtained the agreement of their employees in writing (in electronic format: email, for instance) that they will cease all work in relation to their employment, and must have kept this on record. The Treasury Direction has removed this requirement for agreement in writing, instead stating the agreement between employer and employee must specify the main terms and conditions upon which the employee will cease all work in relation to their employment. Besides, this agreement must be incorporated into the employee's contract, be made or confirmed in writing by the employer and a record of it has to be kept until 30 June 2025.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>Is the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme a public fund for immigration purposes? </td>
            <td>Payments under the Scheme are not public funds and claims can be made for employees on all categories of visas.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="cells">
            <td>What do I need to do to apply to the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </td>
            <td>To make a claim under the scheme, you need: a) to be registered for PAYE online; b) your UK bank account number and sort code (only provide bank account details where a BACS payment can be accepted); c) the billing address on your bank account (this is the address on your bank statements); d) your employer PAYE scheme reference number; e) the number of employees being furloughed and each employee�s National Insurance number (you will need to search for their number if you do not have it or contact HMRC if your employee does not have a number); f) each employee�s payroll or employee number (optional); g) the start date and end date of the claim; h) the full amounts that you�re claiming for including: employee wages; employer National Insurance contributions; employer minimum pension contributions; i) your phone number; j) contact nameYou also need to provide either:- your name (or the employer�s name if you�re an agent) or- your Corporation Tax unique taxpayer reference or- your Self Assessment unique taxpayer reference or- your company registration number</td>
        </tr>
